	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Senegal: what future for EU fisheries access?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 November 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> The signing of a fisheries agreement between Senegal and the EU would be a response to political, diplomatic, economic and commercial issues, according to Dr Ndiaga Gueye, former Senegalese director of fisheries (but now the head of the international institutions and liaison service unit in the FAO Fisheries Department), in an interview on December 27th 2004 in the Senegalese daily <i> Le Soleil. </i> </p><p> Dr Gueye emphasised that 'despite talk in the EU about the need to conserve resources, EU concerns are mainly about the profitability of EU fleets. Such concerns are understandable, but they need to make their rhetoric coherent with their actions.' He also said that: 'one has to admit that fisheries agreements today are an indicator of the weaknesses inherent in the resource-management system, and because of these weaknesses they play an aggravating role in inefficient conservation regimes that are poorly controlled'.</p><p> He highlighted the environmental and socio-economic crisis facing the Senegalese fisheries sector, which, unless appropriate measures are taken quickly, threaten the survival of the sector. He drew attention to the fact that most efforts and foreign financial support in the past were devoted to supporting the production aspect of fisheries, whilst ignoring resource-management aspects. 'There is an imbalance between the resources invested for developing production-related activities, and those invested for resources management,' he said.</p><p> A five-year World Bank project was approved at the end of October to address these kinds of concerns. The GIRMaC (integrated marine and coastal resource management) project is designed to manage marine and coastal resources in Senegal. In announcing this project, the World Bank emphasised that 'the project will help shift the focus from fisheries-sector development to the sustainable management of fish resources, with an emphasis on sharing the responsibilities for management between the government and the fishing communities in a collaborative, or co-management system'.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://www.lesoleil.sn/print.cfm?articles__id=45524" target="_self">Interview in <i>Le Soleil</i>, Dakar, December 27th 2004</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.environnement.gouv.sn/projets/girmac-docs.html" target="_self">Programme de gestion intégrée des ressources marines et côtières (GIRMaC...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.environnement.gouv.sn/pdf/dpn/girmac-en.pdf" target="_self">World Bank, GIRMaC, project concept document</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Senegal has developed a dynamic fisheries sector that directly or indirectly employs some 600,000 people. However, inadequate management of the resources has triggered a crisis that threatens the sustainability of the artisanal fisheries, including the high levels of employment and exports dependent upon them, as well as the coastal ecosystems that support them. As pointed out by Dr Gueye, EU access to coastal resources has aggravated the situation.</p><p> The GIRMaC project that recently gained the support of the World Bank has the ambition to change the situation. But as mentioned in the socio-economic assessment study, there are too many small-scale fishermen, and some of them will have to leave the sector. The question is 'where to'? Many new-comers in the Senegalese artisanal sector have entered only as a last resort, and unless some long-term alternative sources of employment are provided for these people, they will continue fishing even if they have to resort to illegal activities.</p><p> It is to be hoped that the World Bank project will strike the right balance between the need for conservation and management of the resources on the one hand, and the need to meet the social and economic development objectives in fisheries-dependent coastal communities on the other. Also, in promoting collaborative co-management with fishing communities, the World Bank project must not fall into the trap of devolving management responsibilities without building up the local capacity to manage the resources effectively. Co-management involves both the sharing of management responsibilities and sharing the power to manage. This involves both legal and financial dimensions.</p><p> In a situation in which coastal communities will have to face a reduction in the numbers of fishers, it would be difficult for Senegal to grant access to coastal resources to distant-water fleets. If the EU is serious about promoting sustainable development, it will not seek access to these resources in such a situation.</p><p> This issue is of general concern to many ACP countries with thriving small-scale fishing sectors: local sectors cannot be expected to accept restrictions on access to resources if, at the same time, access is granted to the same resources to foreign fleets. This is the case for the cephalopods fishery in Mauritania.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

